answers.body_markdown:
It turned out that in our case we used a `ForkJoinPool` around all this and **we had to configure its *saturate predicate***:

This all happened in our JUnit5 tests where we use a custom [ParallelExecutionConfiguration](https://junit.org/junit5/docs/5.9.0/api/org.junit.platform.engine/org/junit/platform/engine/support/hierarchical/ParallelExecutionConfiguration.html). This executes our tests in parallel by the use of `ForkJoinPool`.

Luckily the mentioned interface provides a new method 
[getSaturatePredicate()](https://junit.org/junit5/docs/5.9.0/api/org.junit.platform.engine/org/junit/platform/engine/support/hierarchical/ParallelExecutionConfiguration.html#getSaturatePredicate()) starting with JUnit 5.9.0. So all we had to do is to upgrade JUnit5 and implement this method:

    @Override
    public Predicate&lt;? super ForkJoinPool&gt; getSaturatePredicate() {
        return forkJoinPool -&gt; true;
    }

